69 (d) All government entities shall cooperate with the authority in the administration of this
70 Code section. Reserved."
71 SECTION 3.
72 Said title is further amended in Chapter 1, relating to general provisions, by adding a new
73 Code section to read as follows:
74 "50-1-14.
75 (a) As used in this Code section, the term:
76 (1) 'Private activity bond' shall have the same meaning as set forth in 26 U.S.C. Section
77 141 of the Internal Revenue Code. Such term shall not include bonds, notes, or
78 obligations subject to the volume cap under 26 U.S.C. Section 146 of the Internal
79 Revenue Code or bonds as defined in Code Section 36-82-182.
80 (2) 'State charter school facility' means real property, personal property, or both, used or
81 intended for use in connection with the operation of a state charter school, as such term
82 is defined in paragraph (5) of Code Section 20-2-2081.
83 (b) The Attorney General is designated as an applicable elected representative, as provided
84 for in 26 U.S.C. Section 147(f)(2)(E) of the Internal Revenue Code, who may approve the
85 issuance of one or more private activity bonds to finance or refinance a state charter school
86 facility after a public hearing following reasonable notice in accordance with 26 U.S.C.
87 Section 147(f) of the Internal Revenue Code and applicable state and federal laws and
88 regulations. Within 60 days of receipt by the Attorney General of a written request for a
89 public hearing by a charter petitioner, the Attorney General or his or her designee shall
90 hold such public hearing following notice as required by 26 U.S.C. Section 147(f) of the
91 Internal Revenue Code. Within 30 days of holding such public hearing, the Attorney
92 General shall approve the issuance of such private activity bonds to finance or refinance
93 a state charter school facility if the applicable charter school is authorized by Article 31A
94 of Chapter 2 of Title 20, the applicable charter petitioner that is a party to the charter for
- 4 -

